<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900405-0087</DOCNO><DOCID>900405-0087.</DOCID><HL>   What's News --   World-Wide</HL><DATE>04/05/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1</SO><LP>   GORBACHEV DENOUNCED Estonia's drive for gradualindependence.   In a telephone call to the president of the Balticrepublic, the Kremlin leader criticized a resolutiondeclaring Estonia an occupied state and said Tallinn's callfor step-by-step secession was invalid. The Estonian officialsaid Gorbachev threatened &quot;similar measures as those taken inLithuania.&quot; In Vilnius, Lithuanian lawmakers approved aresolution accusing the Soviet Union of using the army in anattempt &quot;to overthrow&quot; the government of the republic, whichproclaimed its independence three weeks ago.</LP><TEXT>   Secretary of State Baker opened talks in Washington withMoscow's Shevardnadze, who pledged a &quot;wise and fair&quot;resolution to the situation in Lithuania.   ---   ISRAEL'S PERES CLAIMED enough support to form a governingcoalition.   The Labor Party leader, who has been negotiating withsmall political parties since the March 15 collapse of PrimeMinister Shamir's government, said he had enough backing inthe Knesset to form a ruling coalition. He requested aspecial session of the parliament to approve the newgovernment. Peres, who supports U.S. proposals for Mideastpeace talks, refused to name the new coalition members, andradio reports questioned whether he had the needed votes.   Ex-President Carter, who met in Paris with PLO leaderArafat and France's Mitterrand, blamed leaders in the Mideastfor stalled peace efforts.   ---   Bush held talks in Washington with West Germany'sGenscher, who predicted that the Germanys would be reunitednext year. The foreign minister also said the Soviet Unioneventually may agree that a unified Germany should be inNATO. In Bonn, West Germany said it wants a pact on monetaryunion with East Germany by next month.                                                                                                          East German political parties neared formation of anon-Communist government. Officials agreed to ask ChristianDemocrat leader Maiziere to try to build a coalition, and thelegislature is expected to approve the move when it convenestoday.   ---   The House approved a bill requiring the Justice Departmentfor the first time to collect and publish statistics onso-called hate crimes, those that are motivated by prejudicebased on a victim's race, religion, national origin or sexualorientation. The measure, already passed by the Senate, goesto Bush, who is expected to sign it.   ---   Mandela said the African National Congress is committed totalks with South Africa's government, even though the groupcanceled exploratory discussions that had been set for nextweek. He said his meeting today with President de Klerk wouldhelp determine whether both sides are prepared forpower-sharing negotiations.   ---   El Salvador's government met in Geneva withrepresentatives of the country's leftist rebels forU.N.-sponsored talks in a renewed effort to end a 10-year-oldcivil war. Both sides agreed to seek a cease-fire as an&quot;initial objective&quot; toward a negotiated settlement, but theguerrillas linked acceptance of such a truce to politicalchanges.   ---   China's Li asserted that the country's leadership is&quot;united and strong,&quot; and that the public doesn't want arenewal of last year's student-led protests. The premier, inhis first comments since Beijing's crackdown on dissent, alsosaid that former Communist Party chief Zhao was beinginvestigated over his stance during the protests.   ---   Lebanon's rival Christian forces battled in Beirut afterLebanese Forces chief Geagea urged Syrian-backed PresidentHrawi to send army troops into the country's Christianenclave to end two months of fighting. Maronite Catholicclerics, meanwhile, attempted to forge a truce betweenGeagea's militia and forces loyal to Gen. Aoun.   ---   Colombia's President Barco said the suspected leader ofthe Medellin-based cocaine-trafficking operation won't beextradited to the U.S. if he surrenders to authorities. Itwas the first time that Barco, who guaranteed a fair trialfor Pablo Escobar, has made such a pledge since ordering agovernment crackdown on drugs last August.   ---   Khashoggi was portrayed in opening arguments in U.S. courtin New York as a naive businessman who kept in contact withthe Marcoses in 1986 because he was promised a part of ashipload of gold. Prosecutors contended that numerous phonecalls by the Saudi financier to the couple were part of aneffort to cover up alleged racketeering.   ---   Died: Sarah Vaughan, 66, jazz vocalist who was consideredone of the most distinguished singers to rise from the be-bopera, near Los Angeles, Tuesday, of lung cancer. . . . EdwardE. Carlson, 78, ex-chairman of UAL Inc., Tuesday, in Seattle,of cancer.</TEXT></DOC>